# __PROJECT_NAME__

Minimal verified Google Chat application generated by
`googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__`.

## First local success

```bash
npm install
npm test
npm run fixture
npm run inspect
npm run card
npm run doctor
```

The fixture and test are sanitized and require no Google account, credentials,
or network access.

## Configure a live callback

1. Copy `.env.example` to `.env.local` or set the same values in your deployment
   environment.
2. Set `GOOGLE_CHAT_PROJECT_NUMBER` to the numeric project number used as the
   Chat callback audience.
3. Set `GOOGLE_CHAT_APP_USER` to the Chat app's `users/...` resource.
4. Deploy the server and point the Google Chat app configuration at
   `https://YOUR_HOST/chat/events`.
5. Set `GOOGLE_CHAT_ENDPOINT_CONFIGURED=1` only after checking that exact URL
   in Google Cloud Console.
6. Copy `smoke-space.example.json` to the ignored
   `smoke-space.local.json`, then replace its resource placeholders with a
   dedicated space containing no real users.
7. Run `npm run doctor`.

The live server refuses to start without an audience and verifies every Chat
callback before dispatching it. Google Cloud project creation, Chat app
registration, OAuth consent, administrator approval, and deployment remain
explicit operator steps.

Start the configured server:

```bash
set -a
. ./.env.local
set +a
npm run dev
```

Before any write, inspect the guarded smoke plan:

```bash
npx googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__ smoke \
  --metadata smoke-space.local.json
```

Live smoke needs a short-lived user OAuth token with Chat space-read and
message-read/write access, plus an installed app. Keep the token out of
`.env.local` and shell history. The CLI additionally requires
`RUN_LIVE_GOOGLECHATAI_SMOKE=1` and `--live`; it verifies the dedicated space,
sends one mention, checks that the app replies in the triggering thread, and
deletes the prompt.
